<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter subject="Chemistry" id="111" name="The Solid State">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Solids have ____ shape and ____ volume.</text>
            <option id="A">Definite, Definite</option><option id="B">Indefinite, Definite</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Incompressibility and rigidity are key properties.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Constituent particles in solids are held together by ____ forces.</text>
            <option id="A">Strong intermolecular</option><option id="B">Weak gravitational</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Keeps them in fixed positions.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Solids with irregular arrangement of particles are called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Amorphous</option><option id="B">Crystalline</option><option id="C">Polycrystalline</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Greek word 'amorphos' meaning no form.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Solids with regular long-range order of particles are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Crystalline</option><option id="B">Amorphous</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Characteristic sharp melting points.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Pseudosoilds or supercooled liquids are terms for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Amorphous solids</option><option id="B">Crystalline solids</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>They flow slowly over long time (e.g. old glass).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Crystalline solids are ____ (direction dependent properties).</text>
            <option id="A">Anisotropic</option><option id="B">Isotropic</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Physical properties vary with direction.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Amorphous solids are ____ (same properties in all directions).</text>
            <option id="A">Isotropic</option><option id="B">Anisotropic</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Random arrangement cancels out directional bias.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Example of an amorphous solid: ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Glass / Plastic / Rubber</option><option id="B">Quartz</option><option id="C">NaCl</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lack long range order.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Example of a crystalline solid: ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Quartz / NaCl / Diamond</option><option id="B">Glass</option><option id="C">Rubber</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Definite geometric shape.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Melting point of crystalline solids is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Sharp and definite</option><option id="B">Over a range</option><option id="C">Zero</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Uniformity of bond strengths.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Melting point of amorphous solids is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Over a range of temperatures</option><option id="B">Sharp</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Softens gradually.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Smallest repeating unit in a crystal lattice is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Unit cell</option><option id="B">Atom</option><option id="C">Molecure</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Describes the symmetry of the whole crystal.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The 14 possible three-dimensional lattices are ____ lattices.</text>
            <option id="A">Bravais</option><option id="B">Miller</option><option id="C">Kepler</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Named after Auguste Bravais.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of crystal systems in 3D is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">7</option><option id="B">14</option><option id="C">4</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cubic, Tetragonal, Orthorhombic, etc.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Most symmetric crystal system is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cubic</option><option id="B">Triclinic</option><option id="C">Monoclinic</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>a=b=c and all angles 90 deg.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Least symmetric crystal system is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Triclinic</option><option id="B">Cubic</option><option id="C">Hexagonal</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>a!=b!=c and angles != 90 deg.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Simple cubic unit cell has atoms at ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Corners only</option><option id="B">Center and Corners</option><option id="C">Faces and Corners</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Basic primitive cell.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>BCC unit cell stands for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Body Centered Cubic</option><option id="B">Base Centered Cubic</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Atoms at corners + 1 at center of body.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>FCC unit cell stands for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Face Centered Cubic</option><option id="B">Full Centered Cubic</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Atoms at corners + 1 at center of each face.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Total number of atoms per unit cell in BCC is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2</option><option id="B">1</option><option id="C">4</option><option id="D">8</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>1 (center) + 8 x 1/8 (corners).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Total number of atoms per unit cell in FCC is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">4</option><option id="B">2</option><option id="C">3</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>6 x 1/2 (faces) + 8 x 1/8 (corners).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Coordination number in Simple Cubic lattice is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">6</option><option id="B">8</option><option id="C">12</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Number of nearest neighbors.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Coordination number in BCC lattice is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">8</option><option id="B">6</option><option id="C">12</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Center atom touches 8 corners.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Coordination number in FCC/CCP lattice is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">12</option><option id="B">8</option><option id="C">6</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Maximum packing efficiency.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Packing efficiency of FCC is ____%.</text>
            <option id="A">74</option><option id="B">68</option><option id="C">52.4</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Highest for spheres.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Packing efficiency of BCC is ____%.</text>
            <option id="A">68</option><option id="B">74</option><option id="C">52.4</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Intermediate density.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Packing efficiency of SC is ____%.</text>
            <option id="A">52.4</option><option id="B">68</option><option id="C">74</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Loose packing.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Percentage of empty space in FCC is ____%.</text>
            <option id="A">26</option><option id="B">32</option><option id="C">47.6</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>100 - 74.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Relationship between a (edge) and r (radius) for SC: ____.</text>
            <option id="A">a = 2r</option><option id="B">a = 4r / sqrt(3)</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Atoms touch along edge.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Unit cell of NaCl is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">FCC (with Basis)</option><option id="B">BCC</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cl- forms FCC, Na+ in oct voids.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Radius of octahederal void (r) vs atom radius (R) in close packing: ____.</text>
            <option id="A">r = 0.414 R</option><option id="B">r = 0.225 R</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Geometry ratio.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Radius of tetrahedral void vs atom radius: ____.</text>
            <option id="A">0.225 R</option><option id="B">0.414 R</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Smaller gap than octahedral.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of octahedral voids in CCP per N atoms is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">N</option><option id="B">2N</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>1 void per atom ratio.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of tetrahedral voids in CCP per N atoms is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2N</option><option id="B">N</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>2 voids per atom ratio.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Example of solid showing Frenkel defect: ____.</text>
            <option id="A">AgCl / ZnS / AgBr</option><option id="B">NaCl</option><option id="C">KCl</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ion dislocated to interstitial site.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Example of solid showing Schottky defect: ____.</text>
            <option id="A">NaCl / KCl / KBr / AgBr</option><option id="B">ZnS</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Missing pair of ions.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which compound shows BOTH Schottky and Frenkel defects?</text>
            <option id="A">AgBr</option><option id="B">NaCl</option><option id="C">AgCl</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Unique case due to intermediate ion size.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Schottky defect ____ the density of solid.</text>
            <option id="A">Decreases</option><option id="B">Increases</option><option id="C">Doesn't change</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mass is lost from crystal.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Frenkel defect ____ the density of solid.</text>
            <option id="A">Does not change</option><option id="B">Decreases</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ion only moves within crystal.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Crystalline solids belong to category of ____ solids.</text>
            <option id="A">True</option><option id="B">Pseudo</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Physically and chemically distinct definition.</explanation>
        </question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>Property of showing different physical properties in different directions is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Anisotropy</option><option id="B">Isotropy</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Characteristic of crystalline lattice.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of Bravais lattices in Cubic system is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">3 (P, BCC, FCC)</option><option id="B">1</option><option id="C">4</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Classification of 14 lattices.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Crystal system with a = b != c and all angles 90 deg is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Tetragonal</option><option id="B">Orthorhombic</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: White tin.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Crystal system with a != b != c and all angles 90 deg is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Orthorhombic</option><option id="B">Tetragonal</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Rhombic sulfur.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Density (d) of a crystal formula: d = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">(Z x M) / (a^3 x Na)</option><option id="B">(Z x a^3) / M</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mass of unit cell / Volume.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>HCP stands for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Hexagonal Close Packing</option><option id="B">High Centered Packing</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>ABAB pattern.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>CCP stands for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cubic Close Packing</option><option id="B">Center Corner Packing</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>ABCABC pattern, identical to FCC.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Co-ordination number in 1D packing is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2</option><option id="B">1</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Each sphere touches two neighbors.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>In square close packing (2D), co-ordination number is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">4</option><option id="B">6</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>AAA type arrangement.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>In hexagonal close packing (2D), co-ordination number is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">6</option><option id="B">4</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>ABAB type arrangement.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Relationship for BCC: 4r = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">sqrt(3) a</option><option id="B">sqrt(2) a</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Touch along body diagonal.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Relationship for FCC: 4r = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">sqrt(2) a</option><option id="B">sqrt(3) a</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Touch along face diagonal.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Atomic radius of Al (FCC, a=404pm) is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">143 pm</option><option id="B">200 pm</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>404 / (2 x sqrt(2)).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Density of crystal decreases by Schottky defect but electrical conductivity ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Increases</option><option id="B">Decreases</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Vacancies allow ion hopping.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Color in NaCl (due to excess Na) is caused by ____ centers.</text>
            <option id="A">F-centers (Farbe centers)</option><option id="B">P-centers</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Anionic vacancies occupied by electrons.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Yellow color of NaCl, pink of LiCl, violet of KCl are due to ____ centers.</text>
            <option id="A">F-centers</option><option id="B">Impurity</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Excitation of trapped electrons.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Metal deficiency defect examples: ____.</text>
            <option id="A">FeO / NiO</option><option id="B">NaCl</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Variable oxidation states allow missing cations.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Semiconductors with added Group 15 impurities are ____ type.</text>
            <option id="A">n-type (negative / electron rich)</option><option id="B">p-type</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Doping with P or As into Si.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Semiconductors with added Group 13 impurities are ____ type.</text>
            <option id="A">p-type (positive / hole rich)</option><option id="B">n-type</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Doping with B, Al, or Ga.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Paramagnetic materials are ____ by magnetic field.</text>
            <option id="A">Weakly attracted</option><option id="B">Strongly repelled</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to presence of unpaired electrons.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Diamagnetic materials are ____ by magnetic field.</text>
            <option id="A">Weakly repelled</option><option id="B">Attracted</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>All electrons are paired.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Ferromagnetic materials can be ____ magnetized.</text>
            <option id="A">Permanently</option><option id="B">Only temporarily</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Domains align in field and stay aligned.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Antiferromagnetic materials have net magnetic moment of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">Max</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Opposite alignment of equal moments.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Ferrimagnetic materials have ____ net magnetic moment.</text>
            <option id="A">Small / Weak</option><option id="B">Zero</option><option id="C">Large</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Opposite alignment of unequal moments.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Curie temperature is the temp above which ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ferromagnetics become Paramagnetic</option><option id="B">Solid melts</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Thermal energy disrupts domain order.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Silicon and Germanium are examples of ____ semiconductors.</text>
            <option id="A">Intrinsic</option><option id="B">Extrinsic</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Pure state conduction.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Crystal showing piezoelectric effect: ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Quartz</option><option id="B">Silicon</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Voltage from pressure.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Non-stoichiometric defects are found in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Transition metal oxides</option><option id="B">Alkali halides</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Metals with variable valency.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which defect is also called 'Dislocation defect'?</text>
            <option id="A">Frenkel</option><option id="B">Schottky</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ion dislocated from its lattice site.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Schottky defect is more likely in compounds with ____ coordination number.</text>
            <option id="A">High</option><option id="B">Low</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>And similar ionic radii.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Radius ratio (r+/r-) for Octahedral coordination (6) is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">0.414 - 0.732</option><option id="B">0.225 - 0.414</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Stability range.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Radius ratio for Tetrahedral coordination (4): ____.</text>
            <option id="A">0.225 - 0.414</option><option id="B">0.414 - 0.732</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Stability range.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Coordination number of Cs+ in CsCl is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">8</option><option id="B">6</option><option id="C">4</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>BCC type structure (not truly BCC lattice).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Diamond has co-ordination number of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">4</option><option id="B">6</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Tetrahedral carbon atoms.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Graphite co-ordination number: ____.</text>
            <option id="A">3</option><option id="B">4</option><option id="C">6</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Hexagonal layers.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Volume of HCP unit cell is ____ times area of base x height.</text>
            <option id="A">1 (Standard volume definition)</option><option id="B">2</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Geometric property.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Example of a molecular solid: ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ice / Dry Ice (Solid CO2)</option><option id="B">Diamond</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Held by H-bonds or van der Waals.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Unit of Miller indices: ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Dimensionless</option><option id="B">meter</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reciprocal ratios.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Quartz is crystalline, but silica glass is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Amorphous</option><option id="B">CCP</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Chemical identity vs Physical state.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Superconductors have zero ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Electrical resistance</option><option id="B">Temperature</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Occurs below a critical temperature Tc.</explanation>
        </question>
    </medium>
    <hard>
        <question>
            <text>Bragg's equation: n lambda = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2 d sin(theta)</option><option id="B">d sin(theta)</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Constructive interference of X-rays.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Interplanar distance for cubic system: d = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">a / sqrt(h^2 + k^2 + l^2)</option><option id="B">a / (h+k+l)</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Based on geometry of indices.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Effective number of atoms in HCP unit cell is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">6</option><option id="B">2</option><option id="C">12</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>3(inside) + 2x1/2(bases) + 12x1/6(edges).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Radius of octa void in CCP is max ____ percent of sphere radius R.</text>
            <option id="A">41.4</option><option id="B">22.5</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Math derivation limit.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Coordination number in BCC (not cubic system center though) like for metal atoms: ____.</text>
            <option id="A">8</option><option id="B">12</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard central sphere environment.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>ZnO becomes yellow on heating due to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Metal excess defect (trapped electrons)</option><option id="B">Frenkel</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Loss of oxygen leaves excess Zn/electrons.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Conduction in semiconductors is due to ____ and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Electrons and Holes</option><option id="B">Ions</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Carrier types in solid state physics.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>12-16 and 13-15 compounds approximate Group 14 semi-conductors? Yes. Example:</text>
            <option id="A">GaAs (Gallium Arsenide - 13-15)</option><option id="B">NaCl</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Wide usage in high speed electronics.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Zinc blende (ZnS) structure has co-ordination ____.</text>
            <option id="A">4:4</option><option id="B">6:6</option><option id="C">8:8</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Each ion in tetrahedral void of others.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Fluorite (CaF2) structure has co-ordination ____.</text>
            <option id="A">8:4 (Ca:F)</option><option id="B">4:8</option><option id="C">6:6</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ratio depends on formula stoichiometry.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Anti-fluorite (Na2O) structure has co-ordination ____.</text>
            <option id="A">4:8 (Na:O)</option><option id="B">8:4</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reversed ratio of fluorite.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Solid CO2 (Dry ice) is ____ solid.</text>
            <option id="A">Non-polar molecular</option><option id="B">Polar</option><option id="C">Ionic</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Dispersion forces only.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Ice is ____ solid.</text>
            <option id="A">Hydrogen bonded molecular</option><option id="B">Metallic</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Specific dipole attraction.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>SiC (Carborundum) is ____ solid.</text>
            <option id="A">Covalent / Network</option><option id="B">Ionic</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Extremely hard and high MP.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Metallic solids have ____ melting points generally.</text>
            <option id="A">High (except some like Hg/Ga)</option><option id="B">Zero</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Strong metal-metal attraction.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Sea of delocalized electrons explains ____ in metals.</text>
            <option id="A">Lustre, Color, Conductivity</option><option id="B">Fragility</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Movement of free electrons.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Volume of octahedral void is ____ than tetrahedral? No. Void size refers to largest sphere radius possible.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (Ratio 0.414 vs 0.225)</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Geometric capacity.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Holes in n-type semiconductor are ____ carriers.</text>
            <option id="A">Minority</option><option id="B">Majority</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Electrons dominate.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Holes in p-type semiconductor are ____ carriers.</text>
            <option id="A">Majority</option><option id="B">Minority</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Holes dominate.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Dielectric constant of vacuum is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1 (Exactly)</option><option id="B">0</option><option id="C">infinity</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reference value.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>In BCC, atoms touch ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Along body diagonal</option><option id="B">Along edge</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Geometric packing constraint.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>If 'r' is radius of atom and 'a' is edge length of BCC unit cell, then r = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">(sqrt(3) / 4) x a</option><option id="B">(sqrt(2) / 4) x a</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Derived from body diagonal 4r = sqrt(3)a.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>In primitive cubic, volume occupied by spheres is ____ total volume.</text>
            <option id="A">pi / 6</option><option id="B">pi / 8</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>52.4% expressed as fraction.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Atoms per unit cell for element (M=50) with body-centered lattice (a=290pm):</text>
            <option id="A">2</option><option id="B">1</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard BCC atom count.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Mass of unit cell of element X (FCC, edge a, atomic mass M): ____.</text>
            <option id="A">4 x M / Na</option><option id="B">Z x M</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mass of Z atoms.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Schottky defect is more likely if r+ and r- are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Similar (Size compatibility)</option><option id="B">Very different</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Pairs leave easily.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following describes 'ferromagnetic' behaviour correctly?</text>
            <option id="A">Parallel alignment of all domains</option><option id="B">Opposite</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Resulting in huge magnetic field.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Diamagnetism arises from ____ of electron spins.</text>
            <option id="A">Pairing / Cancellation</option><option id="B">Alignment</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Resulting in zero net moment per atom.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Is quartz a network solid?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (SiO2 recursive bond)</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Giant molecule structure.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Packing efficiency of CCP and HCP are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Equal (74%)</option><option id="B">Unequal</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Both are highest packing forms.</explanation>
        </question>
